S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Relating to a features ability to be clearly seen and identified

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: visually conspicuous
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: term applied to an object either natural or artificial which is distinctly and notably visible from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: not visually conspicuous
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an object which is visible from seaward, but is not conspicuous.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Prominent
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An object which is visible from seaward and may be used as a fixing mar, but is not conspicuous

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Water level effect
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The effect of the surrounding water on an object.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: partly submerged at high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: partially covered and partially dry at high water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: always dry
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: not covered at high water under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: always under water/submerged
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: remains covered by water at all times under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: covers and uncovers
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as 'dries or uncovers'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: awash
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: flush with, or washed by the waves at low water under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: subject to inundation or flooding
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area periodically covered by flood water, excluding tidal waters.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: floating
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: resting or moving on the surface of a liquid without sinking

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: waterway distance
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance measured from an origin of a river or canal.The length of the space between two points along a waterway.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Wave length value
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identicalphase) on an electromagnetic wave.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Offset value of X
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Offset value of X for text offset.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Offset value of Y
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Offset value of Y for text offset.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Text Offset
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The offset of the text position from the centroid of the feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Directional Character
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A directional light is a light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Feature Name
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Features Detected
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The uniform assessment of detected features.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A feature in this context is meant to be any object, whether man made or not, projecting above the sea floor, which may be a danger for surface navigation. (Refer IHO document S-44). Features detected does not describe if features were actually detected during a hydrographic survey, but whether the survey had the capacity to detect features.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Fixed Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A active period of a single fixed event or occurrence, as the date range between discrete start and end dates.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The sub-attributes date start and date end must be encoded in the format YYYYMMDD; using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY) and, optionally, 2 digits for the month (MM) (for example April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, the values are replaced with dashes (-). The date range of a recurring event or occurrence must be encoded using the attribute periodic data range.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Frequency Pair
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A pair of frequencies for transmitting and receiving radio signals. The shore station transmits and receives on the frequencies indicated.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Clearance Fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The horizontal clearance measured between two points for a fixed span.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Clearance Open
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The horizontal clearance measured between two points for an opening span.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Position Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a position.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The expected input is the maximum of the two-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the feature. The information may be provided as a string of text or as a file name of a single external text file that contains the text.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: At least one of the sub-attributes file reference or text must be populated.The sub-attribute file reference is generally used for long text strings or those that require formatting, however, there is no restriction on the type of text (except for lexical level) that can be held in files referenced by sub-attribute file reference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Light Sector
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Measured Distance Value
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance value indicated on a distance mark, or the distance between two measured distance marks.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Multiplicity of Features
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The number of features of identical character that exist as a colocated group.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Online Resource
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Information about online sources from which a resource or data can be obtained.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Orientation
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Periodic Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the active period for a seasonal feature (e.g. a buoy), as the dates between its sub-attributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Radar Wave Length
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance between two successive peaks (or other points of identical phase) on an electromagnetic wave in the radar band of the electromagnetic spectrum.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Rhythm of Light
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light/sound and eclipse/silence for all light characteristics or sound signals.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Schedule by Day of Week
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The nature and timings of a daily schedule by days of the week.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the characteristics of a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Additional textual information about a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.The sector limit specifies the limits of the sector In a clockwise direction around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector limit one
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.Sector limit one specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector limit two
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.Sector limit two specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Shape Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the shape of a non-standard topmark.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: No formatting of text is possible within shape information. If formatted text is required, then an associatedtext file referenced by the complex attribute textual description must be used

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Sequence
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light and eclipse for all "light characteristics".

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Speed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Surface Characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The general nature of the material of which the land surface or the seabed is composed.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Survey Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the period of the hydrographic survey, as the time between itssub-attributes.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The sub-attributes date start and date end must be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY)and, optionally, 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specificmonth and/or day is required/known, indication of the month and/or day is replaced with dashes (-).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Telecommunications
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A means or channel of communicating at a distance by electrical or electromagnetic means such as telegraphy, telephony, or broadcasting.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: If no value is populated for the sub-attribute telecommunication service, this means the service is by voice communication.If no value is populated for the sub-attribute telecommunication carrier , this means the service is by land line communication.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Tidal Stream Panel Values
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The direction of the flow and the springs rate from 6 hours before to 6 hours after high water (HW) or low water (LW) at the reference tide station, at hourly or sub-hourly intervals.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Tidal stream value
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A measurement of the direction and velocity of a tidal stream at a given time relative to the reference tide.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Time Intervals by Day of Week
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The regular weekly operation times of a service or schedule.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Topmark
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A characteristic shape secured at the top of a buoy or beacon to aid in its identification.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: update description
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The textual description of changes included in an update.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: - The sub-attribute text is populated with a brief description of the changes made when the Update is applied,e.g.: Navigational aids insertedChanges to depths alongside and new pontoons added

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of Local Magnetic Anomaly
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The value of the deviation from the normal magnetic variation.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Closed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The vertical clearance of a feature in closed condition (for example a closed lifting bridge) measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The vertical clearance measured from the horizontal plane towards a fixed (non-opening) feature overhead.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Vertical clearance fixed must not be used to populate authorized safe clearances.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Open
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The vertical clearance of a feature in opened condition (for example an open lifting bridge) measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Safe
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The safe vertical clearance of a feature measured from the horizontal plane towards the feature overhead.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The complex attribute encodes the vertical uncertainty associated with any vertical measurement.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vessel speed limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The maximum allowed rate of travel for a vessel in an area in knots.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Defined for
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to a specific spatial type(s).

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Defines
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to an information type providing spatial quality information.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Positions
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to a specific cartographically positioned location for text.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Supported by
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the master feature that equipment feature(s) are supported by.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Supports
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the equipment feature(s) supported by a master feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Updates
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to a feature that has been updated.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Component of
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to a part in a whole-part relationship.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Consists of
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the aggregate in a whole-part relationship.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Has auxiliary
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to a feature to which incidental, secondary or supplementary features are related.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Auxiliary to
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to incidental, secondary or supplementary features related to the referenced feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Information provided for
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to a specific feature(s) for which further information is required.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Provides information
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to an object that provides more information about the referencing feature or information type.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Identifies
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: A pointer to a specific feature(s)

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationAssociation.S100FC:name: Additional information
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationAssociation.S100FC:definition: an information association for the binding between at least one instance of a geo feature and an instance of an information type.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Structure/equipment
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a navigation aid equipment feature and the structure that supports it.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Updated information
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between an update information feature and updated feature(s) that it identifies.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Aids to navigation association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational aids and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) that they define.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: ASL aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between an Archipelagic Sea Lane and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Bridge aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: feature association for the binding between a bridge and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Caution area association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a caution area and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) to which the cautionary information applies.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Deep Water route aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a Deep Water route and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Island aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a named group if islands.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Range system aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational tracks and the navigational aids that define the tracks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Text association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a geo feature and the cartographically positioned location for text.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a Traffic Separation Scheme or a Traffic Separation Scheme System and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Two-way route aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a two-way route and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Fairway aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: A feature association for the binding between related fairways comprising a fairway system.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Fairway auxiliary
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: A feature association for the binding between a fairway and related features auxiliary to the fairway.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Pilotage District Association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: A feature association for the binding between a pilotage gistrict and its component pilot boarding places

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Mooring trot aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: A feature association for the binding between a mooring trot and its component parts.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Contact Details
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: Information on how to reach a person or organisation by postal, internet, telephone, telex and radio systems.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Service Hours
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: The time when a service is available and known exceptions.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Non-Standard Working Day
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: Days when many services are not available. Often days of festivity or recreation or public holidays when normal working hours are limited, especially a national or religious festival, etc

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Nautical Information
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: Nautical information about a related area or facility.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Spatial Quality
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: The indication of the quality of the locational information for features in a dataset.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Quality of Non-Bathymetric Data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the quality of the non-bathymetric data exists

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Data Coverage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographical area that describes the coverage and extent of spatial objects.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is intended to support an indication of coverage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigational system of marks
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a specific system of navigational marks applies and/or a common direction of buoyage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Local Direction of Buoyage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which the navigational system of marks has been established in relation to a specific direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Quality of Bathymetric Data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the quality of the bathymetric data exists.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding datum
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of uniform sounding datum.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vertical datum of data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of uniform vertical datum.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Quality of Survey
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the reliability of source survey information exists.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Update information
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Update Information metadata feature is used to represent a change to the information shown.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Magnetic variation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The angle between the magnetic and geographic (true) north at a location, expressed in degrees east or west from the direction of true north.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Local magnetic anomaly
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An anomaly of the magnetic field of the Earth, extending over a relatively small area, due to local magnetic influences.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Coastline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The line where shore and water meet. Although the terminology of coasts and shores is rather confused, shoreline and coastline are generally used as synonyms.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The solid portion of the Earth's surface, as opposed to sea, water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Island Group
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A group of islands, including archipelago's.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land elevation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An elevation is the vertical distance of a point or a level, on, or affixed to, the surface of the earth, measured from a specified vertical datum.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode both spot heights and land (height) contours.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: River
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A relatively large natural stream of water.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'river' describes the area of the river, the object 'river bank' its banks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Rapids
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Portions of a stream with accelerated current where it descends rapidly but without a break in the slope of the bed sufficient to form a waterfall. Usually used in the plural.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Waterfall
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A sudden descent of water over a step in the bed of a river.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: In place names commonly shortened to fall or falls, e.g. Niagara Falls.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lake
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land region
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of natural scenery on land. It is defined by its geographical characteristics and may be known by its proper name.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vegetation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Collections of, or individual plants.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Ice area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of ice over land or water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sloping ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An inclined surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Slope topline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The upper marking of a slope, e.g. the ridge line or the separation line between two different gradients.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tideway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural water course in intertidal areas where water flows during the ebb or flow.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A channel through which a tidal current runs.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Built-up area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing a concentration of buildings and the supporting road or rail infrastructure.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Building
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A free-standing self-supporting construction that is roofed, usually walled, and is intended for human occupancy (for example: a place of work or recreation) and/or habitation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode single buildings, including those with a particular function or service of major interest.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Airport/airfield
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing at least one runway, used for landing, take-off, and movement of aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Runway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined rectangular area, on a land aerodrome, prepared for the landing and take-off run of aircraft along its length.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A site on which helicopters may land and take off (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2232).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Bridge
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure erected over a depression or an obstacle such as a body of water, railroad, etc. to provide a roadway for vehicles, pedestrians or to carry utility services.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A bridge may consist of portions which cover the land and the water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Span Fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fixed component of the deck of a bridge spanning successive bridge piers.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Span Opening
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An opening component of the deck of a bridge spanning successive bridge piers.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Conveyor
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A mechanical apparatus for moving bulk material or people from place to place (as by a moving belt or chain of receptacles).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable Overhead
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A single continuous rope-like bundle consisting of multiple strands of fiber, plastic, metal, and/or glass, which is supported by structures such as poles or pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The cable supports are encoded as pylon/bridge supports (PYLONS).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pipeline Overhead
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A string of interconnected pipes, supported by pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters, used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pylon/bridge support
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A vertical construction consisting, for example, of a steel framework or pre-stressed concrete to carry cables, a bridge, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fence/Wall
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural or man-made barrier used as an enclosure or boundary or for protection.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Railway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A rail or set of parallel rails on which a train or tram runs.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Road
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A road is an open way for the passage of vehicles.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tunnel
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A passage that is open to the atmosphere at both ends, buried under the sea bed or laid over the sea floor or bored under the ground or through mountains.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Landmark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A prominent object at a fixed location which can be used in determining a location or a direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Silo/tank
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An enclosed container, used for storage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Wind Turbine
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A tower and associated equipment that generates electrical power from wind. They can be sited offshore and may be either fixed or floating.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fortified structure
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure for the military defence of a site.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A fortified structure is often disused, decayed or used for non-defence purpose. Such structures range from major castles and forts to minor lookout posts.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Production/storage area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area on land for the exploitation or storage of natural resources.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Checkpoint
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An official place to register, declare or check goods and people.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'checkpoint' does not include facilities such as buildings, gates or other installations.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Hulk
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A permanently moored ship.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pile
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A long heavy timber or section of steel, wood, concrete, etc. forced into the earth which may serve as a support, as for a pier, or a free standing pole within a marine environment.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dyke
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A dyke (or dike) is an artificial embankment to contain or hold back water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Shoreline construction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fixed (not afloat) artificial structure between the water and the land, i.e. a man-made coastline.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Causeway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A raised way across low or wet ground or water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Canal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'canal' describes the area of the canal, the object 'canal bank' describes the banks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Distance mark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A distance mark indicates the distance measured from an origin and consists of either a solid visible structure or a distinct location without special installation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Usually found on canals.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Gate
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure that may be swung, drawn, or lowered to block an entrance or passageway.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode gates that control the flow of water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dam
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A barrier to check or confine anything in motion; particularly one constructed to hold back water and raise its level to form a reservoir, or to prevent flooding.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Crane
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A machine for lifting, shifting and lowering objects or materials by means of a swinging boom or with a lifting apparatus supported on an overhead track.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The position of a sheerlegs or a travelling crane is defined as its resting position.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Berth
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A named or numbered place where a vessel is moored at a wharf.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Mooring/Warping facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The equipment or structure used to secure a vessel.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dry dock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An artificial basin fitted with a gate or caisson, into which vessels can be floated and the water pumped out to expose the vessel's bottom.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Floating dock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A form of dry dock consisting of a floating structure of one or more sections which can be partly submerged by controlled flooding to receive a vessel, then raised by pumping out the water so that the vessel's bottom can be exposed.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pontoon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A floating structure, usually rectangular in shape which serves as landing, pier head or bridge support.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dock area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A dock is an artificially enclosed area within which ships may moor and which may have gates to regulate water level.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Gridiron
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure in the intertidal zone serving as a support for vessels at low stages of the tide to permit work on the exposed portion of the vessel's hull.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Also called 'careening grid'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lock basin
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lock basin is a wet dock in a waterway, permitting a ship to pass from one level to another.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Mooring Trot
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A mooring is a place where a vessel may be secured.A mooring trot is a mooring that is composed of ground tackle, mooring cables, buoys and mooring berths on junction cables.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sea area/named water area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographically defined part of the sea or other navigable waters. It may be specified within its limits by its proper name.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Each sea area is defined independent of any other. Smaller sea areas may be located within larger sea areas.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tidal stream - flood/ebb
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Approximate tidal stream rates given as discrete rate values for flood and ebb flow during springs.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is a horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Current - non-gravitational
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Currents (non-gravitational) include either singly or in combination: ocean currents (wind and/or density driven), inter-oceanic equalising currents, currents of navigable rivers, river outflow effects offshore and other non-tidal flows.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Water turbulence
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The disturbance of water caused by the interaction of any combination of waves, currents, tidal streams, wind, shoal patches and obstructions.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tidal stream panel data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Approximate tidal stream rates given as discrete rate values at a specified interval before or after a high water.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is an alternating horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1169). The object 'tidal stream panel data' encodes data for use in a tidal panel.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A measured water depth or spot which has been reduced to a vertical datum (may be a drying height).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Drying heights (drying soundings) are indicated by a negative value.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dredged area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of the bottom of a body of water which has been deepened by dredging.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Swept Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area that has been determined to be clear of navigational dangers to a specified depth.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth contour
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A line connecting points of equal water depth which is sometimes significantly displaced outside of soundings, symbols and other chart detail for clarity as well as generalization.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Depth contours, therefore, often represent an approximate location of the line of equal depth as related to the surveyed line delineated on the source. Also referred to as depth curve. Drying contours are encoded with negative values.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A depth area is a water area whose depth is within a defined range of values.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Intertidal areas are encoded as depth areas. These do not have to include soundings. The depth range within a depth area is defined by the attributes DRVAL1 and DRVAL2.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth - No Bottom Found
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Upon investigation the bottom was not found at this depth.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Unsurveyed area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area for which no bathymetric survey information is available.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Seabed area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of the sea where the nature of bottom is homogeneous. The nature of bottom includes the material of which it is composed and its physical characteristics.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Generally, it is not possible to define a seabed area by its real extent. For that reason, the characteristics of the seabed area may be represented at one single position.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Weed/Kelp
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Seaweed, any macroscopic marine alge or seagrass (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4589). Kelp is one of an order (laminariales) of usually large, blade-shaped or vine-like brown algae (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2611).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Seaweed is the general name for marine plants of the Algae class which grow in long narrow ribbons (International Maritime Dictionary, 2nd Ed.). Kelp is often an indication of the presence of submerged rocks (IHO Chart Specifications M-4).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sandwave
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A large mobile wave-like sediment feature in shallow water and composed of sand. The wavelength may reach 100 metres, the amplitude may be up to 20 metres.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Spring
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural issue of water or other substances from the earth. One on the bottom of the sea is called a 'submarine spring'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Underwater/awash rock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A concreted mass of stony material or coral which dries, is awash or is below the water surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Wreck
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The ruined remains of a stranded or sunken vessel which has been rendered useless.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: In marine navigation, anything that hinders or prevents movement, particularly anything that endangers or prevents passage of a vessel.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The term is usually used to refer to an isolated danger to navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Foul Ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Areas over which it is safe to navigate but which should be avoided foranchoring, taking the ground or ground fishing.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Discoloured Water
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Unnatural coloured areas in the sea which may or may not indicate the existence of shoals.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishing facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure in shallow water for fishing purposes which can be an obstruction to ships in general.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The position of these structures may vary frequently over time.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Marine farm/culture
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An assemblage of cages, nets, rafts and floats or posts where fish, including shellfish, are artificially cultivated.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Offshore platform
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A permanent offshore structure, either fixed or floating, used in the production of oil or natural gas.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable Submarine
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An assembly of wires or fibres, or a wire rope or chain which has been laid underwater or buried beneath the seabed.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area which contains one or more submarine cables.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pipeline Submarine/On Land
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A connected set of pipes for conveying liquids, slurries, or gases.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857). It must be assumed that the pipes are vulnerable to damage from anchoring or trawling. They may be a potential danger to navigation (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Submarine pipeline area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing one or more pipelines.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Offshore production area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area at sea within which there are production facilities.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigation line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A navigation line is a straight line extending towards an area of navigational interest and generally generated by two navigational aids or one navigational aid and a bearing.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The extent of the navigation line depends on the visibility of the navigational aid(s). The attribute 'orientation' (ORIENT) specifies the orientation of the navigation line measured from the water towards the navigational aid(s). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended track
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A track recommended to all or only certain vessels.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Recommended tracks include all channels recommended for hydrographic reasons to lead safely between shoal depths. The use of such tracks is generally left to the discretion of the mariner and will depend on the vessel's draught, the state of the tide, adequacy of navigational aids and so on (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation.In the case of a two-way recommended track only one value of orientation is encoded (in the attribute ORIENT); the other value can be deduced (i.e. the value in ORIENT + 180 degrees).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Range System
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Navigation system limited in their positioning capability to coastal regions, or those systems limited to making landfall

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fairway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: That part of a river, harbour and so on, where the main navigable channel for vessels of larger size lies.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: It is also the usual course followed by vessels entering or leaving harbours, called 'ship channel'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fairway System
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: That part of a river, harbour and so on, where the main navigable channel for vessels of larger size lies. It is also the usual course followed by vessels entering or leaving harbours, called "ship channel". A fairway system is an aggregation of connected fairway features making up a complex fairway system.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A fairway system is composed of two or more Fairway features that comprise a complex fairway routeing system, for instance a long fairway comprising several bends.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended Route Centreline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A recommended route centreline indicates the 'centreline' of a recommended route.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A recommended route is a route of undefined width, for the convenience of ships in transit, which is often marked by centerline buoys (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4448). A recommended route describes the regulation of navigation for non-hydrographic reasons such as the prevention of collision or the avoidance of pollution risks. It is generally laid down by a national or international authority other than the hydrographic authority. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Two-way route part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A two-way route part is an area of a two-way route within which traffic flow is generally along one bearing (and possibly its reciprocal).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A two-way route is a route within defined limits inside which two-way traffic is established, aimed at providing safe passage of ships through waters where navigation is difficult or dangerous (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5712). The complete two-way route consists of one or more parts depending on the shape of the two-way route. The orientation of the two-way route part is defined by its centerline and is related to the general direction of the two-way route.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Two-Way Route
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route within defined limits inside which two way traffic is established,aimed at providing safe passage of ships through waters where navigation is difficult or dangerous.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended traffic lane part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An optional part of an IMO-adopted routing measure.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Several Hydrographic Offices, in consultation with their Ministries of Transport, have added recommended directions in areas such as the outer approaches to major ports in order to show the best routes for crossing traffic or to minimize head-on encounters.(IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The object 'recommended traffic lane part' indicates the recommended traffic flow e.g., between two TSS, in the entrance areas of a TSS, beside a deep water route. The complete recommended traffic lane consists of one or more parts depending on the various shapes of the recommended traffic lane. The orientation of the recommended traffic lane part is defined by the middle-line of the recommended traffic lane part relating to the general direction of the recommended traffic lane part.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Deep Water Route Centreline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A Deep Water route centreline indicates the centreline of a route, the width of which is not explicitly defined.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A deep water route is a route in a designated area, within defined limits, which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles to a minimum indicated depth of water (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1280). Additional information can be found in IHO Technical Resolution A1.17.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Deep water route part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A part of a deep water route.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A deep water route is a route in a designated area, within defined limits, which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles to a minimum indicated depth of water (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1280). The complete deep water route consists of one or more parts depending on the shape of the deep water route. The orientation of the route part is defined by the middle line of the part relating to the general direction of the deep water route. Additional information can be found in IHO Technical Resolution A1.17.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Deep Water Route
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route within defined limits which has been accurately surveyed for clearance of sea bottom and submerged obstacles as indicated on the chart.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A complete Deep Water route (DW) system are composed of the features Deep Water Route Centreline, Deep Water Route Part and any associated navigation aids that comprise a complex Deep Water Route system.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Inshore traffic zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A routeing measure comprising a designated area between the landward boundary of a traffic separation scheme and the adjacent coast, to be used in accordance with the provisions of the International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Precautionary area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A routeing measure comprising an area within defined limits where ships must navigate with particular caution and within which the direction of traffic flow may be recommended.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation scheme lane part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A traffic separation scheme lane part is an area of a traffic lane in which the direction of flow of traffic is uniform.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A traffic separation scheme is a scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5585). A traffic lane is an area within defined limits in which one-way traffic flow is established (IMO Ships Routeing, 6th Edition). The complete traffic lane may consist of one or more lane parts depending on the shape of the lane.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A traffic separation zone is a zone separating the lanes in which ships are proceeding in opposite or nearly opposite directions; or separating traffic lanes designated for particular classes of ships proceeding in the same direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A traffic separation scheme is a scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation scheme boundary
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The boundary of a traffic separation scheme is the outer limit of a traffic lane part or a traffic separation scheme roundabout.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A traffic separation scheme is a scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5585).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation scheme crossing
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A traffic separation scheme crossing is a defined area where traffic lanes cross.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A traffic separation scheme is a scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5585).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic separation scheme roundabout
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A roundabout is a traffic separation scheme in which traffic moves in a counter-clockwise direction around a specified point or zone.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A traffic separation scheme is a scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 5585).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A scheme which aims to reduce the risk of collision in congested and/or converging areas by separating traffic moving in opposite, or nearly opposite, directions.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Archipelagic sea lane area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Article 53 of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) states that:'an archipelagic State may designate sea lanes ..., suitable for the continuous and expeditious passage of foreign ships ... through ... its archipelagic waters and the adjacent territorial sea. ... All ships ... enjoy the right of archipelagic sea lanes passage in such sea lanes ... [which] include all normal passage routes used as routes for international navigation ... through archipelagic waters'.(Note: references to aircraft and air routes in UNCLOS have been omitted in these extracts from Article 53).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object class Archipelagic sea lane encodes the area of an Archipelagic sea lane.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Archipelagic sea lane axis
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The reference line used to determine the maximum extents of an Archipelagic Sea Lane. It may not indicate the deepest water nor any recommended route or track.Article 53 of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) states that:'an archipelagic State may designate sea lanes ..., suitable for the continuous and expeditious passage of foreign ships ... through ... its archipelagic waters and the adjacent territorial sea. ..... All ships ... enjoy the right of archipelagic sea lanes passage in such sea lanes ... [which] include all normal passage routes used as routes for international navigation ... through archipelagic waters'.(Note: references to aircraft and air routes in UNCLOS have been omitted in these extracts fromArticle 53).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Archipelagic Sea Lane
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Sea lanes designated by an archipelagic State for the passage of ships and aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radio calling-in point
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: On passing a radio callin-in point or crossing a defined line vessels are required to report on VHF to a Traffic Control Centre. The attribute 'orientation' (ORIENT) encodes the orientation of the traffic flow at that point.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Radio calling-in points are established in certain busy waterways and port approaches to assist traffic control.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Ferry route
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route in a body of water where a ferry crosses from one shoreline to another.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A track along which ships may be guided by coastal radar stations in the event of bad visibility. Also known as a radar guided track.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar range
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Indicates the coverage of a sea area by a radar surveillance station. Inside this area a vessel may request shore-based radar assistance, particularly in poor visibility.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Many large ports have a radar surveillance system covering their approaches to provide guidance for vessels, particularly in poor visibility. The maximum range of the system forms an arc or series of overlapping arcs (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A station with a transmitter emitting pulses of ultra-high frequency radio waves which are reflected by solid objects and are detected upon their return to the sending station.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'radar station' is used to encode the technical equipment itself independent of the building or structure where it is installed. This building or structure, e.g. mast, tower, building, radar dome is a different object.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Anchorage area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area in which vessels anchor or may anchor.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Anchor berth
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A designated area of water where a single vessel, sea plane, etc., may anchor.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: In general the anchor berth is defined by the centre point and a swinging circle.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Seaplane Landing Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A designated portion of water for the landing and take-off of seaplanes.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dumping ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A sea area where dredged material or other potentially more harmful material, e.g. explosives, chemical waste, is deliberately deposited.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Military practice area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which naval, military or aerial exercises are carried out. Also called an 'exercise area'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Administration Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined area within which a jurisdiction applies. It may or may not be named.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cargo transhipment area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area designated for the transfer of cargo from one vessel to another.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The transhipment of cargo is often known as 'lightering' and the area may be known as 'lightering area' or 'cargo transfer area'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Caution Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Generally, an area where the mariner has to be made aware of circumstances influencing the safety of navigation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class may be required to identify:a danger, a risk, a rule, or advice -- which is not directly related to a specific object.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Information Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area for which general information regarding navigation, but not directly related to safety of navigation, is available.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Contiguous zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A zone contiguous to a coastal State's territorial sea, which may not extend beyond 24 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The coastal state may exercise certain control in this zone subject to the provisions of International Law.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Continental shelf area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The continental shelf of a coastal State comprises the sea bed and subsoil of the submarine areas that extend beyond its territorial sea throughout the natural prolongation of its land territory to the outer edge of the continental margin, or to a distance of 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured where the outer edge of the continental margin does not extend out to that distance.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Custom zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The area within which national custom regulations are in force.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Exclusive economic zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area, not exceeding 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured, subject to a specific legal regime established in the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea under which the coastal state has certain rights and jurisdiction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishery zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The offshore zone in which exclusive fishing rights and management are held by the coastal nation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The fishery zone commonly coincides with other zones such as: Continental Shelf, Exclusive Economic Zone.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishing ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A water area in which fishing is frequently carried on.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Free port area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A port where certain import and export duties are waived (unless goods pass into the country) to facilitate reshipment to other countries.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Harbour area (administrative)
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The area over which a harbour authority has jurisdiction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Log pond
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A maritime area enclosed with connected floating timbers used as a staging area for sawn logs.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Oil barrier
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A construction to dam oil flow on water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Straight territorial sea baseline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Straight baselines are a system of straight lines joining specified or discrete points on the low-water line, usually known as straight baseline turning points.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A baseline is the line from which the outer limits of the territorial sea and certain other outer limits are measured (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 390).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Territorial sea area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The territorial sea is a belt of water of a defined breadth but not exceeding 12 nautical miles measured seaward from the territorial sea baseline.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Submarine transit lane
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area where submarines may navigate under water or at the surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pilotage district
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a pilotage direction exists. Such directions areregulated by a competent harbour authority which dictates circumstances under which they apply.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Collision regulations limit
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Convention on the International Regulations forPreventing Collisions at Sea, 1972 (COLREGs). The demarcation line between inland navigation rules andinternational navigation rules.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Restricted Area Navigational
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A navigational restricted area is an area where the restrictions have a direct impact on the navigation of a vessel in the area.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Restricted Area Regulatory
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A regulatory restricted area is an area where the restrictions have no direct impact on the navigation of a vessel in the area, but impact on the activities that can take place within the area.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light All Around
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An all around light is a light that is visible over the whole horizon of interest to marine navigation and having no change in the characteristics of the light.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Sectored
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A sectored light is a light having one or more sectors, which have different characteristics across, and sometimes within, each sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Fog Detector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fog detector light is a light used to automatically determine conditions of visibility which warrant the turning on or off of a sound signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Air Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An air obstruction light is a light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Lateral
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral buoy is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Cardinal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal buoy is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary S-32 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Isolated Danger
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A isolated danger buoy is a buoy moored on or above an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Safe Water
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water buoy is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Special Purpose/General
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose buoy is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Emergency Wreck Marking
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An emergency wreck marking buoy is a buoy moored on or above a new wreck, designed to provide aprominent (both visual and radio) and easily identifiable temporary (24-72 hours) first response.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Buoy Installation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An installation buoy is a buoy used for loading tankers with gas or oil.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A buoy is a floating object moored to the bottom in a particular place, as an aid to navigation or for other specific purposes. (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 565).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Beacon Lateral
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral beacon is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Beacon Cardinal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal beacon is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Beacon Isolated Danger
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An isolated danger beacon is a beacon erected on an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Beacon Safe Water
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A safe water beacon may be used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark. (UKHO NP 735, 5th Edition) Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Beacon Special Purpose/General
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose beacon is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A beacon is a prominent specially constructed object forming a conspicuous mark as a fixed aid to navigation or for use in hydrographic survey (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 420). Topmark, light, fog signal, radar reflector and retro-reflector are separate objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Daymark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The identifying characteristics of an aid to navigation which serve to facilitate its recognition against a daylight viewing background.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: On those structures that do not by themselves present an adequate viewing area to be seen at the required distance, the aid is made more visible by affixing a daymark to the structure. A daymark so affixed has a distinctive colour and shape depending on the purpose of the aid.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light float
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A boat-like structure used instead of a light buoy in waters where strong streams or currents are experienced, or when a greater elevation than that of a light buoy is necessary.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The light of a light float is a separate object, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light vessel
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A distinctively marked vessel anchored or moored at a charted point, to serve as an aid to navigation. By night, it displays a characteristic light(s) and is usually equipped with other devices, such as fog signal, submarine sound signal, and radio-beacon, to assist navigation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Also called 'light ship'. The light(s), fog signal etc. of a light vessel is a separate object, handled as with buoys, beacons, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Retroreflector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A means of distinguishing unlighted marks at night. Retro-reflective material is secured to the mark in a particular pattern to reflect back light.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The body carrying the retro-reflector is a separate feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar reflector
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A device capable of, or intended for, reflecting radar signals.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A radar reflector is usually a tetrahedron or pentagonal corner reflector to facilitate reflection towards the sender.(International Maritime Dictionary, 2nd Ed.). The object 'radar reflector' is only used to encode a device specifically intended to reflect radar signals. If any other object, e.g. topmark, buoy, beacon, etc. is radar conspicuous, because of its construction, the attribute 'CONRAD' must be used.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fog signal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A warning signal transmitted by a vessel, or aid to navigation, during periods of low visibility. Also, the device producing such a signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Physical AIS aid to navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from a physical Aid to Navigation, or transmitted from an AIS station for an Aid to Navigation which does or does not physically exist.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Virtual AIS Aid to Navigation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) message 21 transmitted from an AIS station to simulate on navigation systems an Aid to Navigation which does or does not physically exist.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radio station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place equipped to transmit radio waves.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Such a station may be either stationary or mobile, and may also be provided with a radio receiver. In British terminology, also called 'w/t station'. The transmission of a radio station may serve to provide mariners with a line of position (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The object 'radio station' is used to encode the point of transmission of the signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar transponder beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A transponder beacon transmitting a coded signal on radar frequency, permitting an interrogating craft to determine the bearing and range of the transponder.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object class 'radar transponder beacon' is only used to encode the technical equipment independent of the structure on which it is located (e.g. a beacon, light-vessel or tower).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pilot Boarding Place
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The meeting place to which the pilot comes out.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vessel Traffic Service Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The area of any service implemented by a relevant authority primarily designed to improve safety and efficiency of traffic flow and the protection of the environment. It may range from simple information messages, to extensive organisation of the traffic involving national or regional schemes.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Coastguard station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Watch keeping stations at which a watch is kept either continuously, or at certain times only.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to describe the function of the coastguard rather than the building in which the coastguard is sited.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Signal Station Warning
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A warning signal station is a place on shore from which warning signals are made to ships at sea.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Signal Station Traffic
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A traffic signal station is a place on shore from which signals are made to regulate the movement of traffic.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A signal station is a place on shore from which signals are made to ships at sea (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Rescue station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place at which life saving equipment is held.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object encodes the service available at this location. The structure housing the service should be coded separately.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Harbour facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A harbour installation with a service or commercial operation of public interest.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Small craft facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place at which a service generally of interest to small craft or pleasure boats is available.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class encodes the service available at this location. The structure housing the service should be encoded separately.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Text placement
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The Text Placement feature is used in association with the Feature Name attribute or a light description to optimize text positioning in ECDIS.
